  "github.com/cloudevents/sdk-go/v2/event"
)

func init() {
  functions.CloudEvent("HelloPubSub", helloPubSub)
}

// helloPubSub consumes a CloudEvent message and extracts the Pub/Sub message.
func helloPubSub(ctx context.Context, e event.Event) error {
  // ... (code for handling the Pub/Sub message omitted)
}
```

3. Prepare the application by following the steps in [Source: gcp/Cloud Functions/Terraform Pub/Sub Tutorial > Preparing the application]. This includes cloning the sample app repository and changing to the directory that contains the Cloud Run functions sample code.

To secure an AWS VPC using IAM policies, you can create a policy that specifies conditions for granting permissions to specific instances within the VPC. The policy should use the `ec2:SourceInstanceARN` condition key to specify the ARN of the instance(s) from which requests are allowed.

Here's an example of such a policy [Source: aws/EC2/Example policies for working with the AWS CLI or an AWS SDK<a name="ExamplePolicies_EC2"></a>]:

```json
{
    "Version": "2012-10-17",
    "Statement": [
        {
            "Effect": "Allow",
            "Action": [
                "ec2:Describe*"
            ],
            "Resource": "*",
            "Condition": {
                "StringEquals": {
                    "ec2:SourceInstanceARN": "arn:aws:ec2:region:account-id:instance/i-instance-id"
                }
            }
        }
    ]
}
```

Replace `region`, `account-id`, and `instance-id` with the appropriate values for your VPC. This policy allows an instance to view resources in various AWS services, but only if the request is made from the specified instance.

For more information on IAM policies and best practices, refer to [Policy best practices](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/iam-best-practices.html) in the AWS EC2 User Guide.

To deploy a containerized application on AWS ECS, follow these steps as outlined in the provided documentation:

1. Access the new Amazon ECS console ([Source: aws/ECS/New Amazon ECS console](https://console.aws.amazon.com/ecs/v2)) and create or select an existing cluster. [1]

2. Register a task definition for your application by specifying the compatible launch type (`EC2` or `Fargate`) and container image details. For example, if you're using Fargate, you can use the provided PHP web app container image from DockerHub: [https://hub.docker.com/r/amazon/amazon-ecs-sample](https://hub.docker.com/r/amazon/amazon-ecs-sample) [5]

3. After registering the task definition, deploy your workload on an external instance that has been registered to your cluster. Use the `EXTERNAL` launch type when creating a service or running a standalone task. [2]

4. If you're using EC2 instances, connect to your container instance using the classic console: [3]
   - Select the cluster that hosts your container instance.
   - On the **Cluster** page, choose **Infrastructure**.
   - Under **Container Instance** column, choose the container instance to connect to.
   - Record the **Public IP** or **Public DNS** for your instance.

5. Deploy your application by creating a service using the task definition and launch configuration (EC2 or Fargate) that you created earlier. [4]

6. If you're using AWS CDK to deploy your application on Fargate, define a containerized web server in the stack definition file as shown in the example provided: [5]

```yaml
// In the AWS CDK project, edit the stack definition file

const taskImage = ContainerImage.fromRegistry('amazon/amazon-ecs-sample');

new ecs.FargateTaskDefinition(this, 'MyTaskDefinition', {
  cpu: '256',
  memoryLimitMiB: 512,
  taskRole: role,
  networkConfiguration: new ecs.AwsVpcConfiguration({
    subnets: subnetIds,
    securityGroups: [securityGroup],
    assignPublicIp: true,
  }),
  containerDefinitions: [{
    image: taskImage,
    name: 'MyContainer',
    essential: true,
    portMappings: [{
      containerPort: 80,
      hostPort: 80,
      protocol: Protocol.TCP,
    }],
  }],
});
```

To deploy a containerized application on AWS and send its logs to Amazon CloudWatch, follow these steps based on the provided context [Source: aws/ECS/Using the awslogs log driver<a name="using_awslogs"></a>]:

1. Create a task definition for your application using the `awslogs` log driver. Here's an example of a task definition JSON file with the `awslogs` log driver configuration:

```json
{
  "family": "my-app",
  "containerDefinitions": [
    {
      "name": "my-app",
      "image": "my-docker-image",
      "logConfiguration": {
        "logDriver": "awslogs",
        "options": {
          "awslogs-group": "my/cloudwatch-log-group",
          "awslogs-region": "us-west-2",
          "awslogs-stream-prefix": "ecs"
        }
      },
      ...
    }
  ]
}
```

2. Use the task definition to run your application using the AWS Elastic Container Service (ECS). You can do this through the ECS console, CLI, or API.

3. To view the logs from your containers, go to the CloudWatch Logs console in the AWS Management Console and navigate to your log group specified in the task definition. [Source: aws/ECS/Using the awslogs log driver<a name="using_awslogs"></a>]
